{0 Document synchronization}

How the server keeps its in-memory view of the vault consistent with
disk as the user opens, edits, saves, and closes files.

{1 State}

{ul
  {- [vault]: a {!Oystermark.Vault.t} holding the index, pre-resolved
     docs, and vault root.  Built from disk; rebuilt on didOpen and
     didSave.}
  {- [open_docs]: a set of vault-relative paths for documents the
     editor currently has open.  Used only to know {i which} files
     need diagnostic refresh after a save — {b it does not track
     buffer contents}.}
}

{1 Current behavior}

{b This section describes what the server does today.  The
buffer-vs-disk story is not yet settled — see
{{!section-"open-questions"}Open questions} below.}

Feature handlers (find references, inlay hints, go-to-definition,
hover) read document content from disk via [read_file].  If the user
has unsaved edits, those features may return stale results until the
next save.

Diagnostics are computed against the live buffer content passed in
notification payloads, so squigglies update as the user types.

{1 Notification handling}

{2 [textDocument/didOpen]}

{ol
  {- Add the document's rel_path to [open_docs].}
  {- Rebuild the vault from disk.  This catches files that were added
     out-of-band since the last rebuild.}
  {- Publish diagnostics for the opened document, computed against
     [content] from the notification.}
}

{2 [textDocument/didChange]}

Recompute and publish diagnostics for the changed document against
[new_content].  Nothing else happens — [vault] is {i not} rebuilt
and feature handlers continue to see the pre-edit disk state.

{2 [textDocument/didSave]}

{ol
  {- Rebuild the vault from disk.  The saved file's new content is
     now part of the vault, along with any other files that changed
     on disk as a side-effect of the save.}
  {- For every entry in [open_docs], read its current disk content
     and republish diagnostics.  This is what clears stale warnings
     in sibling buffers when the save caused them to become
     resolvable.}
}

{2 [textDocument/didClose]}

Remove the entry from [open_docs].  No rebuild.

{1 Observable consequences}

{ul
  {- Unsaved edits don't affect features other than diagnostics.
     Adding a new [[[note-x]]] link to an unsaved buffer and
     immediately running find-references on [note-x] will not show
     the new link.}
  {- Diagnostics for the active buffer are live — the squiggly under
     an unresolved link appears and disappears as the user types.}
  {- Diagnostics for sibling buffers refresh only on save.  If [a.md]
     is open with an unresolved [[[b]]] link, creating [b.md] in
     another tab only clears [a.md]'s warning once a save fires.}
  {- Out-of-band file changes (e.g. [git checkout]) are only picked
     up on the next didOpen or didSave.}
}

{1:open-questions Open questions}

{ul
  {- {b Should feature handlers honor unsaved buffer content?}  Doing
     so means holding a server-side copy of every open buffer and
     incrementally re-resolving links on didChange.  The current
     behavior is simpler but can surprise users who expect
     find-references to reflect what they see on screen.  Not yet
     decided.}
  {- {b Should diagnostics recompute on didChange at all?}  Keeping
     them live is ergonomic but inconsistent with the rest of the
     feature set answering from disk.  The alternative is to refresh
     everything only on save.}
}
